##You can't be an "iron rooster" when you get through tough times

We must guard tightly and return to work at once

You can't be an "iron rooster" when you get through tough times

-- Yan Xiaofeng

Published in the 938th issue of China Newsweek on March 9,2020

The new coronavirus has swept away retail, restaurants, tourism, and now manufacturing. "Made in China" is the foundation of the country, if they do not do production, production can not be shipped out, that is more than the epidemic of the national disaster.

China concept shares led the plunge on Wall Street in the past two days. This is the darkest hour for China's economy.

"I'm going to lose a million a quarter, " said one of my boss friends, who owns a small and medium-sized food-processing business. As of February 25, his company's resumption rate reached 3040% , in the industry is good. He's not worried about his company going out of business, but he's worried that everyone from the VP down to the employees isn't on his side now. Vice Presidents get paid, employees get paid, and government taxes and social security are paid. Every penny counts. How's HE GONNA do that?

The boss's current problem is not only that everyone is not in the same boat, but also difficult to recruit workers. Of the seventy thousand workers at Foxconn in Zhengzhou, only about 5,000 are now employed. The workers would not be able to get out and would be quarantined for 14 days. They would also be afraid that if they got infected, it would be a family disaster.

The dining hall eats the food to be infected, the dormitory sleeps to be infected, that is big. That would be "diamond princess" cruise mode, totally enclosed, highly contagious. I see Huawei staff canteen is to take set meal, everyone to the side to eat quietly, no longer the usual lively scene.

In response, my boss friend's practice is to isolate all workers who return to work, are not allowed to go home, in the factory to eat, work, sleep, once found problems can be dealt with in a timely manner. Because in the event of an outbreak, all the costs would be borne by the boss, not the government.

Another way is to return to work by installments, the wages of those who work, the living expenses of those who wait for a post. The cost of living, 80% of the local minimum wage, is now backed by government documents. The boss said that the general enterprises are not willing to lay off employees, lay-off is also not allowed, because once laid-off may not be able to recruit people, so the best way is to pay living expenses first.

What is needed to overcome the difficulties is the joint efforts of everyone, who should not be the iron rooster. Businesses collapsed, workers had to find new jobs, and the government had no tax revenue. You can't just yell "Gas" and not do anything.

The big part of this is still with the government. At the macro level, we are happy to see governments at all levels extend a helping hand to msmes. In addition to tax reduction and social security, cities such as Beijing, Guangzhou and Shenzhen have responded quickly and introduced a series of support policies.

But it's hard to get back to work! 21 papers to return to work somewhere. The People's Daily came out and said: Give me a hand, don't put your hand out. And Zhejiang and other places in order to help enterprises resume work, government departments to charter a plane, Charter cars, package high-speed rail back to migrant workers, not only subsidized food, housing, send masks, but also a living allowance. In contrast, there is a difference in the level of governance.

Of course, local governments are right to worry about the risks of resuming work. By the end of February, 10m workers in Guangdong alone had not returned to work. According to incomplete statistics, 12 clusters of outbreaks occurred in Guangdong after the resumption of work, 15 people were diagnosed, more than 514 people were quarantined. In some places, factories and offices are closed in case of an epidemic, and the losses are borne by businesses. Relevant officials may be removed from their posts.

Local officials are now facing seemingly contradictory orders to defend and resume work. My boss friend said he was particularly sympathetic to the government's difficulties. The central government suppresses the local government, of course the local officials should suppresses the enterprises, but who should the enterprise owners supplant? That's the problem with their bosses. "close it! Or real estate, or stocks. " This of course is sarcastic.

As for the loss of production in the first quarter of this year, Yu Jianrong suggested on Weibo that the government should bear a third, enterprises a third and employees a third. I commented that it is both realistic and necessary for businesses, employees and the state to share the losses in the face of adversity, because you have to understand that without businesses, everyone has to live on borrowed time.

Duty Editor: Zhuang Menglei
